INSERT INTO notes VALUES('2fa99354-f997-4e69-8280-6c069223ed26','Function argument and parameter difference',replace('\nx = ''banana''\ny = max(x)\nz = y * 2\n\nIn the given code, there is only one function call, which is max(x).\n\nIn this context, x is the argument, because it is the value that is being passed to the function. The argument is the actual value that is passed to a function when it is called.\n\nThe function max() takes one parameter, which is the value that it expects to receive as an argument. In this case, x is the parameter of the max() function, because it is the variable that is declared within the function definition and represents the value that the function operates on.\n\nSo, to summarize:\n\nx is the argument that is passed to the max() function.\nmax() takes x as its parameter, because x is the value that the function operates on.\n\n\nIn the given code, the argument that is passed to the max() function is the variable x. The value of x is the string ''banana'', which is a sequence of characters. ''banana'' is the value of the argument.','\n',char(10)),'2023-03-10 23:01:37',NULL,'');
