INSERT INTO notes VALUES('1fe9dfb5-f622-414b-a315-7ad6fc230460','what encode and decode do in socket programming',replace('\nIn socket programming, the terms "encode" and "decode" refer to the process of converting data from its original format to a format suitable for transmission over a network (encoding) and converting the received data back to its original format (decoding).\n\nEncoding: When sending data over a network using sockets, the data needs to be encoded into a byte stream. This is necessary because networks transmit data in the form of binary data (bytes). The encoding process involves converting the data from its native representation (such as strings, integers, or objects) into a sequence of bytes that can be transmitted.\n\nCommon encoding techniques in socket programming include:\n\n1. String encoding: Converting strings to byte sequences using specific encoding schemes like UTF-8 or ASCII.\n2. Serialization: Converting complex data structures or objects into a binary representation that can be transmitted.\n\nDecoding: On the receiving end, the data received over the network is in the form of a byte stream. To make sense of this data and work with it in the desired format, decoding is performed. Decoding involves converting the received byte stream back into its original data format.\n\nCommon decoding techniques in socket programming include:\n\n1. String decoding: Converting byte sequences back into strings using the same encoding scheme used during encoding.\n2. Deserialization: Converting the received binary representation back into the original data structure or object.\n\nThe encoding and decoding processes ensure that data can be transmitted accurately and efficiently over a network using sockets. It allows applications on different machines to communicate by converting data into a common format that can be understood on both ends of the network connection.\n\nReference: https://www.coursera.org/learn/python-network-data/lecture/MbRIS/12-3-unicode-characters-and-strings','\n',char(10)),'2023-05-23 03:16:42',NULL,'');
INSERT INTO notes VALUES('b8436a68-c533-4501-bba3-5d452a3d726b','what is unicode and utf 8',replace('Unicode is a character encoding standard that aims to assign a unique numeric value (code point) to every character in all writing systems used around the world, regardless of the platform, program, or language. It provides a universal character set that encompasses a vast range of characters, including letters, digits, symbols, and special characters from various scripts and languages.\n\nUTF-8 (Unicode Transformation Format-8) is a variable-length character encoding scheme that is widely used to represent Unicode characters in computer systems. It can represent any character in the Unicode standard, yet it remains backward-compatible with ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange). UTF-8 uses one to four bytes to encode characters, depending on the character''s code point value. It is designed to be space-efficient and compatible with ASCII, making it the most commonly used character encoding on the web.\n\nIn UTF-8, ASCII characters (with code points 0 to 127) are represented using a single byte (8 bits), preserving their compatibility with the ASCII encoding. Characters outside the ASCII range are represented using multiple bytes, where the leading bits of each byte indicate it is part of a multi-byte sequence. The variable-length nature of UTF-8 allows it to represent a vast number of Unicode characters while efficiently using storage space.\n\nUTF-8 has become the dominant character encoding for web-based communication, as it supports multilingual content and provides compatibility with existing ASCII-based systems. It allows applications, platforms, and programming languages to handle and transmit text in various languages and scripts seamlessly.\n\nencode() make sure that data to byte stream\ndecode() make sure that corresponding encoding technique(say UTF-8 or asii) to unicode','\n',char(10)),'2023-05-23 03:11:42',NULL,'');
