INSERT INTO notes VALUES('a9b121cc-4fa9-41b5-837d-ef8e60631bce','',replace('what is seeing with tongue?\n\nSeeing with the tongue, also known as "sensory substitution," is a technique that involves using a device to convert visual information into tactile(connected with sense of touch) or auditory signals that can be perceived by other senses, such as touch or hearing.\n\nFor example, a device called "The vOICe" can convert visual information into a series of sounds that can be interpreted by the user through headphones. The device uses a camera to capture visual information and then converts that information into a pattern of sound that the user can learn to interpret as a visual scene.\n\nAnother example of sensory substitution is the use of a tongue display unit (TDU), which converts visual information into electrical signals that can be felt by the tongue. The TDU consists of a small camera mounted on a pair of glasses, and a small electrode array that is placed on the tongue. The camera captures visual information and then sends it to the electrode array, which stimulates the tongue with electrical pulses in a way that the user can learn to interpret as visual information.\n\nSensory substitution can be helpful for people with visual impairments, as it provides an alternative way of perceiving the world around them. It can also be used for other applications, such as remote sensing or military surveillance.','\n',char(10)),'2023-02-24 20:14:42',NULL,'');
